1. A × B ∪ B × A

A × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}
B × A = {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}

A × B ∪ B × A = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}

2. B × A ∪ A × B

B × A = {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}
A × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

B × A ∪ A × B = {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

Comparing the sets obtained in step 1 and step 2:

A × B ∪ B × A = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}
B × A ∪ A × B = {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

The two sets are equal. This means that the union of the Cartesian products A × B and B × A is commutative, i.e., A × B ∪ B × A = B × A ∪ A × B. However, this does not imply that the Cartesian product itself is commutative, as A × B ≠ B × A in general.
